I&#x27;m usually not much of a Java fan, but making bool a stricter type was a good change.  I always write my C code as if it had the same rules.  For example, if you have:<p><pre><code>    bool b;
    int i;
    unsigned u;
    void *p;
</code></pre>
You could write code that looked like:<p><pre><code>    if (b && i && u && p)
</code></pre>
...and some people would even consider that idiomatic.  I&#x27;d write the same test as:<p><pre><code>    if (b && (i != 0) && (u > 0) && (p != NULL))
</code></pre>
which is a little longer but, IMO, clearer.  If the compiler enforced that style this family of bug would happen a lot less.<p>In a similar vein, I wish enums had strict conversion rules.  C++11 finally gives us that with &quot;enum class&quot;, but I don&#x27;t think anything similar exists in C.
